'''Ronald Federico Araújo da Silva''' ({{IPA|es|roˈnald aɾaˈuxo}};<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 November 2023 |title=Conferencia de prensa de Ronald Araújo y Darwin Núñez |trans-title=Press conference of Ronald Araújo and Darwin Núñez |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A_zYCYQraF4&t=4s |access-date=3 December 2025 |via=YouTube |publisher=[[Teledoce]] |language=es}}</ref> born 7 March 1999) is an Uruguayan professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre-back]] for {{Spanish football updater|Barcelona}} club [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], whom he [[Captain (association football)|captains]], and the [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay national team]].

==Club career==
===Rentistas===
Araújo joined [[C.A. Rentistas|Rentistas]] from hometown club Huracán de Rivera.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ovaciondigital.com.uy/futbol/ronald-araujo-boston-river-barcelona.html|title=Ronald Araújo: de Boston River a Barcelona|trans-title=Ronald Araújo: from Boston River to Barcelona|publisher=Ovación|language=es|date=28 August 2018|access-date=3 September 2018}}</ref> He made his senior debut with the former on 24 September 2016, coming on as a late [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 1–0 [[Uruguayan Segunda División|Segunda División]] away win against [[Tacuarembó F.C.|Tacuarembó]].

Araújo scored his first senior goal on 9 December 2016, netting the equaliser in a 2–2 home draw against [[Central Español]]. He became a regular starter during the 2017 season, and scored a [[hat-trick]] in a 3–2 away win over [[C.S.D. Villa Española|Villa Española]] on 17 June of that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elascenso.com/destacados/villa-espanola-2-rentistas-3/|title=Villa Española 2 Rentistas 3|publisher=El Ascenso|language=es|date=17 June 2017|access-date=3 September 2018}}</ref>

It was at Rentistas that Araújo made the significant switch in position from forward to defender.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Lowe |first1=Sid |last2=@sidlowe |date=23 February 2023 |title=Barcelona's Ronald Araújo: 'I came from a different football. But I told myself, I have to play here' |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/feb/23/barcelonas-ronald-araujo-i-came-from-a-different-football-but-i-told-myself-i-have-to-play-here |access-date=23 February 2023 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

===Boston River===
On 28 July 2017, Araújo joined [[Uruguayan Primera División|Primera División]] side [[Boston River]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tenfield.com.uy/ronald-araujo-ya-es-de-boston/|title=Boston River: llega Ronald Araújo|trans-title=Boston River: Ronald Araújo arrives|publisher=[[Tenfield]]|language=es|date=28 July 2017|access-date=3 September 2018}}</ref> He made his debut in the category on 18 September, replacing [[Maximiliano Sigales]] late into a 1–0 home success over [[El Tanque Sisley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tenfield.com.uy/boston-river-00-el-tanque-sisley/|title=Boston River volvió a festejar, 1:0|trans-title=Boston River celebrate again, 1–0|publisher=Tenfield|language=es|date=18 September 2017|access-date=3 September 2018}}</ref>

===Barcelona===
On 29 August 2018, Araújo signed a five-year contract with [[La Liga]] club [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] for a fee of [[Euro|€]]1.7 million, plus €3.5 million in variables; he was initially assigned to [[FC Barcelona B|the reserves]] in [[Segunda División B]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.es/futbol/barca-b/noticias/2018-2019/acuerdo-con-el-boston-river-para-el-traspaso-de-ronald-araujo?_ga=2.224128731.1587900172.1535999485-1095797129.1535999485|title=Acuerdo con el Boston River para el traspaso de Ronald Araujo|trans-title=Agreement with Boston River for the transfer of Ronald Araujo|publisher=FC Barcelona|language=es|date=29 August 2018|access-date=3 September 2018}}</ref> He made his first team – and [[La Liga]] – debut on 6 October of the following year, coming off the bench to replace [[Jean-Clair Todibo]] in the 73rd minute of a 4–0 home win against [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]]; however, he was sent off in the 86th minute for fouling [[Javier Hernández]].<ref>[https://en.as.com/en/2019/10/06/football/1570396360_867051.html Dembélé and Araújo sent off during Barcelona win over Sevilla]; ''[[Diario AS]]''. 6 October 2019, Retrieved 18 August 2020</ref>

For the [[2020–21 FC Barcelona season|2020–21 season]], Araújo was promoted to the main squad, being handed the number 4 jersey, which was previously worn by [[Ivan Rakitić]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://as.com/futbol/2020/10/05/primera/1601923973_013966.html|title=Riqui Puig y Araújo ya son jugadores del primer equipo|trans-title=Riqui Puig and Araújo are already first team players|publisher=Diario AS|language=es|date=5 October 2020|accessdate=18 October 2020}}</ref> On 19 December 2020, he scored his first [[La Liga]] goal for Barcelona in a 2–2 home draw against [[Valencia CF|Valencia]].<ref name=":0">{{cite web |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/barcelona/2020/12/19/5fde40c946163f2e908b45e4.html |title=Araujo is a man of many talents |website=Marca |date=19 December 2020 }}</ref>

On 20 March 2022, Araújo scored his first goal in [[El Clásico]], heading in a corner from [[Ousmane Dembélé]] in a 4–0 away victory against the league leaders at [[Santiago Bernabéu Stadium|Santiago Bernabéu]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Barcelona thrash leaders Real Madrid |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/60816848 |access-date=20 March 2022 |work=BBC Sport |date=20 March 2022}}</ref>

For the first 21 league games of the [[2022–23 FC Barcelona season|2022–23 season]], Araújo formed a defensive partnership alongside [[Andreas Christensen]] and occasionally [[Jules Koundé]] at centre-back, helping Barcelona keep the most clean sheets (16) in all of [[Big Five (association football)|Europe's top 5 leagues]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronald Araujo vital as Barcelona nab 16th clean sheet, push LaLiga title further from Real Madrid|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/barcelona-espbarcelona/story/4876613/barcelona-nab-18th-clean-sheet-grip-laliga-title-over-real-madrid |work=ESPN |date=13 February 2023}}</ref>
[[File:Ronald Araujo i Gavi amb els polos de passeig que inclouen la marca Catalunya (28-07-2023) (Ronald Araújo).jpg|thumb|Araújo with [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in 2023]]
On 21 July 2023, Barcelona announced Araújo as the club's third captain.<ref>{{Cite web |title=FC Barcelona's new captains confirmed |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/football/first-team/news/3599643/fc-barcelonas-new-captains-confirmed |access-date=26 July 2023 |website=www.fcbarcelona.com |language=en}}</ref> On 4 November 2023, he scored his first goal of the [[2023–24 La Liga|2023–24 season]] in the 92nd minute of stoppage time in a 1–0 away win over [[Real Sociedad]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/la-liga/articles/ronald-araujo-scores-only-goal-as-barcelona-snatch-win-over-real-sociedad-2023-11-04 |title=Ronald Araujo scores only goal as Barcelona snatch win over Real Sociedad |publisher=beIN SPORTS |date=4 November 2023}}</ref>

On 16 April 2024, Araújo received a straight red card for fouling [[Bradley Barcola]] in the first-half of Barcelona's Champions League quarter-final second leg match against [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] which shifted the momentum in PSG's favor, turning the tide of the match despite Barcelona's two goal lead and eventually ended up losing 4–1 on the night, and 6–4 on aggregate.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Xavi: 'Araujo red card changed everything' |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/football/first-team/news/3970394/xavi-araujo-red-card-changed-everything/featured |access-date=17 April 2024 |website=www.fcbarcelona.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=16 April 2024 |title=Ronald Araujo's red card turned UEFA Champions League tie in Paris Saint-Germain's favour, says Rio Ferdinand |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/champions-league/2023-2024/ronald-araujo-s-red-card-turned-uefa-champions-league-tie-in-paris-saint-germain-s-favour-says-rio-f_sto10105517/story.shtml |access-date=17 April 2024 |website=Eurosport |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/barcelona-psg-ronald-araujo-red-32603251|title=Ronald Araujo gesture explained as furious Barcelona star sent off during PSG showdown|publisher=The Mirror|date=16 April 2024}}</ref> On 23 January 2025, he extended his contract with the club until 2031.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/football/first-team/news/4202872/ronald-araujo-renews-contract-with-fc-barcelona-until-2031 |title=Ronald Araujo renews contract with FC Barcelona until 2031 |publisher=FC Barcelona |date=23 January 2025 }}</ref>

On 18 October 2025, in a La Liga match against [[Girona FC|Girona]], Araújo came on as a substitute [[Marc Casadó]] in the second-half and scored the winning goal in a 2–1 home win in stoppage time.

On 25 November 2025, Araújo was heavily criticized during a UEFA Champions League away fixture against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]. He had earned a yellow card in the 32nd minute and then just 12 minutes later Araújo fouled defender [[Marc Cucurella]] in which the referee gave Araújo a second yellow card and was sent-off before the end of the first-half. Barcelona would go on to lose the match 3–0 in which many pundits and sports journalists blamed Araújo for disrupting the flow of the match.

==International career==
After representing [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] at [[Uruguay national under-17 football team|under-18]] and [[Uruguay national under-20 football team|under-20]] levels, Araújo received his first call up for the senior side on 5 October 2020, for two [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2022 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]] against [[Chile national football team|Chile]] and [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/fc-barcelona/20200305/473976093569/primera-convocatoria-de-ronald-araujo-con-la-absoluta-de-uruguay.html|title=Primera convocatoria de Ronald Araujo con la absoluta de Uruguay|trans-title=First call up of Ronald Araújo with the full side of Uruguay|publisher=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|language=es|date=5 March 2020|access-date=18 October 2020}}</ref> He made his full international debut eight days later, starting in a 2–4 loss against the latter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/fc-barcelona/20201014/484053950703/-ecuador-barre-a-la-uruguay-de-suarez-valverde-y-araujo.html|title=Ecuador barre a la Uruguay de Suárez, Valverde y Araujo (4–2)|trans-title=Ecuador beat Suárez, Valverde and Araújo's Uruguay (4–2)|publisher=Mundo Deportivo|language=es|date=14 October 2020|access-date=18 October 2020}}</ref>

In June 2021, Araújo was included in the final 26-man Uruguay squad for the [[2021 Copa América]] in Brazil, but he didn't feature in any of Uruguay's five games in the tournament while also suffering a muscle injury.<ref>{{cite web|title=Plantel de Uruguay para la Copa América|trans-title=Uruguay squad for the Copa América|publisher=auf.org|language=es|url=https://www.auf.org.uy/plantel-de-uruguay-para-la-copa-america/|date=10 June 2021|access-date=19 July 2021}}</ref>

Despite nursing an injury, Araújo was included in the Uruguay squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], having expected a recovery during the knockout phase.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/news/2903008/araujo-included-in-uruguay-squad|title=Araujo included in Uruguay squad|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=10 November 2022|access-date=10 December 2022}}</ref> However, he did not make an appearance as Uruguay were eliminated in the group stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/dec/02/ghana-uruguay-world-cup-group-h-match-report|title=Uruguay beat Ghana but crash out of World Cup on goals scored in late twist|work=The Guardian|date=2 December 2022|access-date=10 December 2022}}</ref>

On 16 November 2023, he scored his first goal with the national team against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]] fifth round at [[La Bombonera]] in [[Buenos Aires]]. In the 41st minute, Araújo received the ball after a [[Matías Viña]]'s low cross into the penalty box and beat Argentine keeper [[Emiliano Martínez]] with a shot from the right side of the goal to the bottom left corner.<ref>{{cite news |language=es |url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/mundial/nota/_/id/12878737/ronald-araujo-abrio-marcador-uruguay-argentina-clasico |title=Ronald Araujo abrió el marcador para Uruguay ante Argentina |date=16 November 2023 |work=[[ESPN]] |access-date=17 November 2023}}</ref>

On 31 May 2026, Araújo was named in Uruguay's 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mundial 2026: Uruguay dio a conocer la lista de 26 convocados por Marcelo Bielsa|url=https://www.montevideo.com.uy/Deportes/Mundial-2026-Uruguay-dio-a-conocer-la-lista-de-26-convocados-por-Marcelo-Bielsa-uc963756|language=es|date=31 May 2026|access-date=31 May 2026}}</ref>

== Style of play ==
Originally a striker, Araújo's physicality made his youth coaches move him to centre-back at age 17.<ref name="breakingthelines.com">{{Cite web |date=22 May 2022 |title=Ronald Araujo: Barcelona's Uruguayan Colossus in Defense - Breaking The Lines |url=https://breakingthelines.com/player-analysis/ronald-araujo-barcelonas-uruguayan-colossus-in-defense/ |access-date=15 December 2024 |language=en-GB}}</ref> Primarily a right-footed centre-back, Araújo is also comfortable playing as a right-back, a role in which he has been deployed on occasion to counter skilled wingers. Known for his defensive solidity, Araújo excels in one-on-one duels and has an ability to time his challenges effectively. His pace and athleticism allow him to recover quickly and cover large spaces, making him an invaluable asset in high defensive lines.<ref>{{Cite web |date=25 February 2023 |title=Is Ronald Araújo the best central defender in the world? His level and his rivals to the 'title' |url=https://www.fcbarcelonanoticias.com/en/players/ronald-araujo-best-center-back-world-level-big-rivals-title_289974_102.html |access-date=16 December 2024 |website=FCBN |language=en}}</ref>

Brazilian winger [[Vinícius Júnior]] has called him <nowiki>''The best defender I have ever faced. He's very strong and very good''</nowiki>.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Fleming |first=Rob |date=13 April 2023 |title=Real Madrid's Vinicius Jr hails Barcelona's Ronald Araujo as best defender ever faced |url=https://www.planetsport.com/soccer/news/la-liga-real-madrids-vinicius-hails-barcelonas-ronald-araujo-best-defender-ever-faced |access-date=15 December 2024 |website=PlanetSportcom |language=en}}</ref>

Standing at 1.91 meters, Araújo is dominant in the air, both defensively and offensively. His aerial prowess makes him a constant threat from set pieces, where his ability to outjump opponents has led to crucial goals for both club and country.<ref name="breakingthelines.com"/>

Despite his defensive strength, his ball-playing abilities have often been criticized. During the Champions League quarter-final, Luis Enrique stated that he ordered his men to press Araújo when he had the ball.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Clark |first=Gill |date=15 October 2024 |title=Luis Enrique's brutal verdict of Barcelona defender Ronald Araujo revealed |url=https://www.barcablaugranes.com/2024/10/15/24269743/luis-enriques-brutal-verdict-of-barcelona-defender-ronald-araujo-revealed |access-date=15 December 2024 |website=Barca Blaugranes |language=en}}</ref> Araújo's defensive decision-making has also been lacking as he sometimes lacks positional sense, and the sense of when to intercept and when to be proactive.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ronald Araujo: La Liga Player Watch |url=https://learning.coachesvoice.com/cv/ronald-araujo-barcelona-ronald-koeman/ |access-date=15 December 2024 |website=Coaches' Voice |language=en-GB}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Araújo was born in Uruguay to a [[Brazilian Uruguayans|Brazilian-Uruguayan]] father and a Brazilian mother in [[Rivera]], a city near the Brazilian border.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/deportes/2020-10-03/ronald-araujo-el-velocista-que-se-mira-en-puyol.html|title=Ronald Araujo, el velocista que se mira en Puyol|first=Jordi|last=Quixano|language=es|website=El País|date=3 October 2020|accessdate=3 February 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sport.es/es/noticias/barca/ronald-araujo-el-central-humilde-que-el-real-madrid-no-pudo-birlar-8151257|title=Ronald Araujo, el central humilde que el Real Madrid no pudo 'birlar'|first=German|last=Bona|language=es|website=Sport|date=11 October 2020|accessdate=3 February 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/barcelona/2020/12/21/5fdfabe7ca4741273c8b4606.html|title=Ronald Araujo: un soldado de Dios que esprinta a 35km/h y está bendecido por los jefes|website=Marca|language=es|first=Hugo|last=Cerezo|date=21 December 2020|accessdate=3 February 2021}}</ref> He is [[Christians|Christian]].<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |date=21 December 2020 |title=Ronald Araujo: God's soldier who runs 35 km/h |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/barcelona/2020/12/21/5fe0834eca4741c2518b456d.html |access-date=4 December 2023 |website=MARCA |language=en}}</ref>

In 2016, he began a relationship with Abigail Olivera, whom he married on 21 July 2025, at the Methodist Temple of Montevideo.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-06-23 |title=Boda de Ronald Araujo y Abigail Olivera: emotiva ceremonia en una iglesia metodista y gran fiesta secreta |url=https://www.elpais.com.uy/tvshow/personajes/boda-de-ronald-araujo-y-abigail-olivera-emotiva-ceremonia-en-una-iglesia-metodista-y-gran-fiesta-secreta |access-date=24 July 2025 |website=EL PAIS |language=es-UY}}</ref> Together, they are the parents of two daughters: Aitana (b. 2021) and Adara (b. 2024).<ref>{{Cite web |last=König |first=Kosta |date=2 February 2024 |title=Ronald Araujo celebrates addition to his family |url=https://tribuna.com/en/news/fcbarcelona-2024-02-02-ronald-araujo-celebrates-addition-to-his-family/ |access-date=24 July 2025 |website=Tribuna.com}}</ref>

In late 2025, Araújo traveled to Jerusalem for a mental health break as a result of heavy criticism for his performance in a 3–0 loss against Chelsea. He returned to training about a month later.{{Citation needed|date=April 2026}}

